me cases this is also an Americanized form of the rare Danish and Norwegian cognate <b>Bengtsen</b>."]},{"name":"Bankston","meanings":["Americanized form of Swedish   Bengtsson  . Compare   Bankson  .","History: Andrew Bankston, alias Anders Bengtsson, came to New Sweden on the Delaware river in 1656; he died in Philadelphia, PA, in 1706."]},{"name":"Bengston","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Helmer, Nels, Nils.","Altered (metathesized) form of Swedish   Bengtsson  ."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bankson","meanings":["Americanized form of Swedish   Bengtsson  . Compare   Bankston  ."]}]},{"name":"Birger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse: apparently an agent derivative of <i>biarga</i> ‘to help’. Earlier forms of the name are <i>Birghir</i> and <i>Byrghir</i>. It has been in use from the Viking period to the present day, and it may in some cases have been chosen as a masculine form of   Birgit ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Brosa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of English <b>Rose</b>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702072,"age":17,"year":"1100","julianDay":2122827,"title":"Vreta Abbey is First Christian Convent","description":"Vreta Abbey was established around 1100 and was the first Christian convent in Sweden. It was located in modern-day Linkoping Municipality. It was founded on orders of Pope Paschal II with large donations by King Inge the Elder and Queen Helena.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Birger Brosa Bengtsson was born in Sweden as the son of Bengt Snivil and Ulfhild Bjørnsdotter. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Brigida Haraldsdatter. He died on 9 January 1202, in Visingsö, Jönköping, Sweden."},"et":{"–9 January 1202":"–9. jaanuar 1202","1150–1208":"1150–1208","–1202":"–1202","–1220":"–1220","1130–1209":"1130–1209","–1200":"–1200","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1120–1177":"1120–1177","1202":"1202","1200":"1200","9 January 1202":"9. jaanuar 1202","1100":"1100","1177":"1177","1220":"1220","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1177":"umbes 1177","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Sweden":"Rootsi","Sverige":"Rootsi","Visingsö, Jönköping, Sweden":"Visingsö, Jönköping, Rootsi"},"fi":{"–9 January 1202":"–9. tammikuuta 1202","1150–1208":"1150–1208","–1202":"–1202","–1220":"–1220","1130–1209":"1130–1209","–1200":"–1200","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1120–1177":"1120–1177","1202":"1202","1200":"1200","9 January 1202":"9. tammikuuta 1202","1100":"1100","1177":"1177","1220":"1220","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1177":"noin 1177","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Sweden":"Ruotsi","Sverige":"Ruotsi","Visingsö, Jönköping, Sweden":"Visingsö, Jönköping, Ruotsi"},"fr":{"–9 January 1202":"–9 janvier 1202","1150–1208":"1150–1208","–1202":"–1202","–1220":"–1220","1130–1209":"1130–1209","–1200":"–1200","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décé